    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "One note at line 25 only — line 17 is too early",
    "content": "One note at line 25 is sufficient. Do not add a note at line 17.\n\nReasoning: At line 17, the author self-glosses 境界 as 界限. The reader is being told \"bounds\" and the passage is about the limits of language. At this point in the essay, 境 as a technical concept has not yet been introduced -- the reader has no frame to receive the information \"境界 contains 境.\" Telling them \"this word contains a character that will become important later\" is a forward reference with no anchor. It creates a cognitive debt the reader cannot yet pay off.\n\nAt line 25, the author *themselves* performs the separation -- writing 境界 in the main clause and bare 境 in the parenthetical. This is the natural place for the note because the text itself is doing the work. The translator's note at line 25 merely makes explicit what the author is already showing. The reader now has both terms in front of them simultaneously and can absorb the relationship.\n\nOne well-placed note that arrives at the moment of insight is worth more than two notes that arrive too early and on time."
  }
}
